To represent transferable knowledge through the lens of Bloom's
Taxonomy, you cannot use a simple unstructured Brainstorming or Mind
Map. Those usually flatten information into a single layer of
importance.

Instead, the specific kind of map that reflects Bloom's Taxonomy is a
#strong[Hierarchical Concept Map] (or a #strong[Layered Knowledge
Graph];).

This map is structured #strong[vertically] or #strong[concentrically];,
moving from concrete facts at the bottom (or center) to abstract
connections and creations at the top (or outer edges).

Here is how you construct a knowledge map that mirrors the six levels of
Bloom's Taxonomy:

== 1. The Structure: From Surface to Deep
<the-structure-from-surface-to-deep>
In a standard mind map, all nodes are roughly equal. In a
#strong[Bloom's Map];, the visual depth represents cognitive depth.

=== Level 1: Remembering ( The Nodes)
<level-1-remembering-the-nodes>
- #strong[Map Element:] #strong[Isolated Nodes/Data Points.]
- #strong[What to map:] Definitions, formulas, dates, keywords.
- #strong[Visual:] Single words or boxes at the bottom of the page or
  the very center of the map.
- #emph[Example:] A node labeled "Supply" and a node labeled "Demand."

=== Level 2: Understanding (The Local Links)
<level-2-understanding-the-local-links>
- #strong[Map Element:] #strong[Labeled Connections (Propositions).]
- #strong[What to map:] Explaining #emph[why] two nodes are next to each
  other. You must label the line.
- #strong[Visual:] Short lines connecting the Level 1 nodes.
- #emph[Example:] Drawing a line between "Supply" and "Demand" labeled
  "interact to determine price."

=== Level 3: Applying (The Clusters)
<level-3-applying-the-clusters>
- #strong[Map Element:] #strong[Grouping/Zoning.]
- #strong[What to map:] Placing concepts into a specific context or
  scenario to solve a problem.
- #strong[Visual:] Drawing a boundary circle around a group of nodes and
  labeling the group with a use-case.
- #emph[Example:] Grouping Supply, Demand, and Price nodes inside a box
  labeled "Market Mechanism," then drawing an arrow to a box labeled
  "Housing Crisis" to show application.

=== Level 4: Analyzing (The Cross-Links)
<level-4-analyzing-the-cross-links>
- #strong[Map Element:] #strong[Long-range Bridges.]
- #strong[What to map:] Drawing connections between distinct, seemingly
  unrelated branches of the map to show patterns, cause-and-effect, or
  contradictions. This breaks the linear hierarchy.
- #strong[Visual:] Dashed lines cutting across the map, often colored
  differently (e.g., Red for "Contradicts," Blue for "Correlates with").
- #emph[Example:] Connecting "Market Mechanism" in the Economics branch
  to "Social Inequality" in the Sociology branch to analyze the
  relationship between efficiency and equity.

=== Level 5: Evaluating (The Annotations)
<level-5-evaluating-the-annotations>
- #strong[Map Element:] #strong[Visual Coding/Tagging.]
- #strong[What to map:] Judgments on the value, validity, or quality of
  the information.
- #strong[Visual:] Using color codes (e.g., Green = Proven, Red =
  Debunked) or adding "sticky note" icons to nodes with critiques.
- #emph[Example:] Marking the "Efficient Market Hypothesis" node with a
  question mark or a specific color indicating "Contested Theory."

=== Level 6: Creating (The Restructuring)
<level-6-creating-the-restructuring>
- #strong[Map Element:] #strong[The Meta-Map / New Branch.]
- #strong[What to map:] Taking the existing nodes and rearranging them
  entirely to form a new model or hypothesis.
- #strong[Visual:] A new, separate section of the map where elements are
  combined in a novel way to propose a solution.
- #emph[Example:] Drawing a new branch called "Sustainable Economics"
  that combines "Supply/Demand" with "Environmental Constraints" (from a
  Biology branch) to create a new circular economy model.

