== Visual Layouts to Use
<visual-layouts-to-use>
To physically draw this, you can choose one of two distinct layouts:

=== A. The "Tree of Knowledge" (Vertical Hierarchy)
<a.-the-tree-of-knowledge-vertical-hierarchy>
- #strong[Bottom:] The roots are facts (Remembering).
- #strong[Trunk:] The main concepts (Understanding).
- #strong[Branches:] Applications of concepts (Applying).
- #strong[Cross-pollination:] Vines connecting different branches
  (Analyzing).
- #strong[Fruit:] New ideas generated from the synthesis (Creating).

=== B. The "Onion" (Concentric Map)
<b.-the-onion-concentric-map>
This is best for transferable knowledge systems (systems thinking). \*
#strong[Center Core:] Key Definitions (Remember). \* #strong[First
Ring:] Relationships and processes (Understand). \* #strong[Second
Ring:] Contexts where this applies (Apply). \* #strong[Outer Ring:]
Links to external systems (Analyze/Evaluate).

== Summary
<summary>
If you want a map that reflects Bloom's Taxonomy, #strong[you must
insist on labeled relationships.] \* A map with just words is a
#strong[Remembering] map. \* A map with unlabeled lines is an
#strong[Understanding] map. \* A map with labeled lines ("causes,"
"prevents," "requires") that connect distant concepts is an
#strong[Analyzing] and #strong[Creating] map.
